Regression Project: Boston House Price Prediction¶

Marks: 60¶

Welcome to the project on regression. We will use the Boston house price dataset for this project.

Objective¶

The problem at hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features affecting the price of the house. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for the unseen data.

Dataset¶

Each record in the database describes a house in Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below:

Attribute Information:

  • CRIM: Per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: Proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: Proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: Nitric Oxide concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: The average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: Proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: Weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: Index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: Full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: Pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

# Function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, title="Distribution of Feature", figsize = (12, 7), kde = False, bins = None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows = 2,      # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex = True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize = figsize,
    )                   # Creating the 2 subplots

    # Add the title to the figure (above both subplots)
    f2.suptitle(title, fontsize=14)
    sns.boxplot(
        data = data, x = feature, ax = ax_box2, showmeans = True, color = "violet"
    )                   # Boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2, bins = bins, palette = "winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2
    )                   # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color = "green", linestyle = "--"
    )                   # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color = "black", linestyle = "-"
    )

Data Preprocessing¶

  • We see no missing values that need treatment.
  • Let's do some log transformation on the MEDV to account for a slight bit of skewness.
  • A number of our features are scaled differently (e.g. NOX vs TAX). Let's apply scaling to our model to attempt to improve our performance.
  • No feature engineering is REQUIRED since all the data is numeric but as you will see below, we will combine a few columns to address some multicollinearity issues.
  • Outliers seem to to be valid data points. Treatment of them could lead to biased results.
  • We'll need to split our independent variables and target variable.

Model Building - Linear Regression¶

First, lets include a few handy functions we can use for model evaluation.

In [367]:
# Function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# Function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# Function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    pred = model.predict(predictors)                  # Predict using the independent variables
    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)                       # To compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)    # To compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # To compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)           # To compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)                   # To compute MAPE

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Function to check VIF
def checking_vif(train):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = train.columns

    # Calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(train.values, i) for i in range(len(train.columns))
    ]
    return vif

print(checking_vif(x_train1))

Key Observations¶

  1. Overall Model Fit
  • R-squared (0.783): This indicates that the model explains 78.3% of the variance in the median house value (MEDV). This is a relatively good fit, suggesting the predictors have substantial explanatory power.
  • Adjusted R-squared (0.777): This adjusts the R-squared for the number of predictors in the model. It's slightly lower than the R-squared, indicating that some predictors might not contribute significantly to explaining the variance.
  • F-statistic (117.8) and Prob (F-statistic) (1.02e-121): The F-statistic tests the overall significance of the model (i.e., whether at least one of the predictors is significantly related to MEDV). The extremely low p-value (<0.05) strongly suggests that your model as a whole is statistically significant.
  1. Significant Predictors

The following predictors have p-values less than 0.05 and are therefore considered statistically significant at the conventional level:

  • CRIM: crime rate (negative relationship)
  • ZN: proportion of residential land zoned for large lots (positive relationship)
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise) (positive relationship)
  • NOX: nitric oxides concentration (negative relationship)
  • RM: average number of rooms per dwelling (positive relationship)
  • DIS: weighted distances to five Boston employment centers (negative relationship)
  • RAD: index of accessibility to radial highways (positive relationship)
  • TAX: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000 (negative relationship)
  • PTRATIO: pupil-teacher ratio by town (negative relationship)
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population (negative relationship)
  1. Non-Significant Predictors
  • INDUS: proportion of non-retail business acres per town (p-value > 0.05, not significant)
  • AGE: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940 (p-value > 0.05, not significant)
  1. The Variance Inflation Factors (VIF) for a number of the predictors indicate some degree of multicollinearity.

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

Checking the below linear regression assumptions¶

In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

  1. Mean of residuals should be 0
  2. No Heteroscedasticity
  3. Linearity of variables
  4. Normality of error terms
In [386]:
# Mean of residuals should be near zero
residuals = olsmodel2.resid
np.mean(residuals)

5.386230515508185e-16

Observations:

  • The mean of residuals is very close to 0. Hence, the corresponding assumption is satisfied.
  • Since p-value > 0.05, we cannot reject the Null Hypothesis that the residuals are homoscedastic and the corresponding assumption is satisfied.
  • From the above plots, the residuals seem to follow a normal distribution. Hence, the corresponding assumption is satisfied. Now, we will check the model performance on the train and test datasets.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Based on our linear regression model's summary, here are some actionable insights we can derive to understand and predict housing prices in the Boston area:

Key Factors Influencing Median Home Values (MEDV):¶

  • Crime Rate (CRIM): A higher crime rate significantly lowers median home values. This aligns with the common intuition that safer neighborhoods are more desirable and thus have higher property values.

  • Proportion of Residential Land Zoned for Large Lots (ZN): A higher proportion of large-lot residential areas tends to increase median home values, potentially due to the perception of greater space and exclusivity.

  • Charles River Proximity (CHAS): Homes located near the Charles River tend to have higher median values. This could be attributed to scenic views, recreational opportunities, or other desirable aspects associated with riverside living.

  • Average Number of Rooms (RM): A higher average number of rooms per dwelling is strongly associated with higher median home values. This is intuitive, as larger homes generally command higher prices.

  • Pupil-Teacher Ratio (PTRATIO): A lower pupil-teacher ratio (indicating smaller class sizes and potentially better schools) is associated with higher median home values. This highlights the importance of education quality in housing decisions.

  • Percent Lower Status of the Population (LSTAT): A higher percentage of lower-income residents is strongly associated with lower median home values. This likely reflects socioeconomic factors influencing housing affordability and desirability.

  • (RADTAX) This combined variable, representing the product of accessibility to radial highways (RAD) and property tax rate (TAX), has a positive coefficient. This suggests that areas with higher accessibility to highways and/or higher property taxes tend to have higher median home values. This might be due to the convenience of highway access being valued even with the associated higher taxes.

  • Distance to Employment Centers and Nitric Oxide Concentration (DISNOX): A higher value of this combined variable, indicating greater distance from employment centers and higher pollution levels, is linked to lower median home values. This likely reflects the desirability of living closer to jobs and in less polluted areas.

Investment/Policy Decisions¶

The insights can inform real estate investment strategies, urban planning decisions, and policy-making. For example, investing in areas with lower crime rates, proximity to the Charles River, good schools, and lower pollution levels might yield higher returns.

Homebuyers/Sellers¶

Individuals can use this information to make more informed decisions about buying or selling properties. They can prioritize neighborhoods with desirable characteristics based on the model's coefficients.

Recommendations¶

We should consider non-linear models such as Random Forest or XGBoost to refine the analysis and gain deeper insights.
